Duck typing is a programming concept where an object's methods and properties determine its compatibility with a certain interface or type, rather than its specific type. In other words, if an object has the same shape (methods and properties) as another object, it can be treated as that type.

In TypeScript, duck typing is implemented through structural typing. Structural typing is a typing system where the type of an object is determined by the values of its properties and methods, rather than their names or the type of the object itself. This means that two objects with the same structure can be considered of the same type, even if they have different types.

For example, consider the following TypeScript code:

```typescript
interface Bird {
  fly(): void;
}

interface Bat {
  fly(): void;
  eatBugs(): void;
}

function identify(animal: Bird | Bat) {
  if (animal.eatBugs) {
    console.log("This is a bat.");
  } else {
    console.log("This is a bird.");
  }
  animal.fly();
}

const myBird: Bird = {
  fly: () => console.log("Flying..."),
};

const myBat: Bat = {
  fly: () => console.log("Flying..."),
  eatBugs: () => console.log("Eating bugs..."),
};

identify(myBird); // This is a bird.
identify(myBat); // This is a bat.
```

